consideration from previous teleological representations of catastrophes as an endpoint, and to begin considering their "operative" aspects, which unmask the nature of social and political structures. Among the essays in this volume are analyses, by leading scholars in their respective fields, concerning the role of catastrophes in theology, in the history of industrial accidents, in theory of history, in the history of law, in "catastrophe films", in the history of cybernetics, in post-Holocaust discussions of reparations, and in climate change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDisastersxHistory. 0aDisastersxSocial aspects. 4aKritische Theorie. 4aKulturgeschichte. 4aNaturkatastrophen. 4aNotsituation. 4aWissenschaftsgeschichte. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBates, David W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattistoni, Alyssa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoen, Deborah R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDörries, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzog, Dagmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorn, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKavka, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKillen, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKillen, Andreas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLebovic, Nitzan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLebovic, Nitzan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook p